State MSM Profile: North Carolina

Background & Methods

In 2015-2016, researchers at Emory University partnered with colleagues at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) to develop methods to estimate the number of men who have sex with men (MSM) residing in each county in the United States. Using population and housing data from the American Community Survey and estimates from two peer-reviewed publications (Oster et al., 2015 & Purcell et al., 2012), they derived an indirect estimate of MSM population sizes that took into account both the urbanicity of the county as well as its density of households with a male householder and a male same-sex partner.

The full methodology is published in the Journal of Medical Internet Research - Public Health and Surveillance:

Grey JA, Bernstein KT, Sullivan PS, Purcell DW, Chesson HW, Gift TL, Rosenberg ES. Estimating the population sizes of men who have sex with men in US states and counties using data from the American Community Survey. JMIR Public Health Surveill 2016;2(1):e14. DOI: 10.2196/publichealth.5365

Overview of MSM in North Carolina

An estimated 103,009 men who have sex with men (MSM) resided in North Carolina in 2013, representing 2.3% of the 4,503,084 MSM in the United States. Of the 3,536,017 adult men of North Carolina, 2.9% had had sex with another man in the past 5 years, which was less than the overall percentage of adult men in the United States who were MSM (3.9%).

Most MSM in North Carolina resided in central counties of large metropolitan areas (38.8%). Including both central and fringe counties, 51.6% resided in a large metropolitan area.


Percentage of MSM by urbanicity, United States and North Carolina, 2013

MSM in North Carolina Counties

Among counties or county-equivalent areas in North Carolina, Mecklenburg County had the largest population of MSM at 20,920, representing 20.3% of all MSM in the state. Swain County had the highest percentage of MSM among adult men in North Carolina at 10.1%. This was greater than the percentage for North Carolina as a whole, which was 2.9% of adult men.

Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.



MSM in North Carolina Metropolitan Statistical Areas

Charlotte-Concord-Gastonia Metropolitan Statistical Area

The Charlotte-Concord-Gastonia MSA overlaps two states: North Carolina and South Carolina. The North Carolina portion of the MSA had the largest metropolitan population of MSM in North Carolina at 31,581, or 30.7% of all MSM in the state and 89.0% of the 35,470 MSM in the MSA. Of the 685,029 adult men in the North Carolina part of Charlotte-Concord-Gastonia, an estimated 4.6% were MSM. This was greater than the percentage of MSM among adult men in the MSA as a whole, which was 4.4% of adult men (35,470 out of 807,928).



Note: Range cutpoints for the map are based on the distribution of MSM among all counties in the United States.
